@node "Introduction"

                                Introduction

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Bridgeboard is a full length Zorro II board that fits into one of the combined 
Zorro/PC AT slots in the A2000, A3000(T) and A4000(T) amigas.

It provides a PC-on-a-card for virtually 100% compatability, and at full speed.

At this time there are two "makes" of bridgeboards;

	Commodore	The A2088, A2286 and A2386 boards 
			providing 8088, '286 and '386 emulations respectively

	Vortex		The 'Golden Gate' GG386 and GG486 boards
			providing '386 and '486 emulations respectively

This guide deals with (for the most part) the Commodore A2386 card.

N.B. both these companies no longer build these boards...Escom?
...however,

A company has just begun to supply the following, but I dont have much 
information on it;

486/50Mzh DX2, expandable upto 128MB on board
I/O serial/parallel, keyboard connector for PC keyboards,
on board IDE and floppy controller. Goes into any ISA slot. 

Contact: Chua Kian Tong <ktchua@teleview.com.sg>

		----------------

The Commodore card allows you to share:
  Amiga memory as PC memory (via external @{"software" link software})
  Amiga and PC hard disks,
  The Amiga's parallel ports,
  The Amiga's disk drives,


The Vortex card allows you to share:
  Amiga memory as PC memory and vice versa,
  Amiga hard disks,
  The Amiga's serial/parallel ports,
  The Amiga's disk drives,

..This card also has a "server mode" where the amiga can use
the PC's ports/disks and memory(?!).
  
@endnode
@node "Common Problems"

I also had problems installing the PC Janus software. It doesn't completely 
install if you follow the instructions in the guide, which tell you to 
enter "xcopy a:\janus c:\janus".  After typing that, you must also type 
"xcopy a:\dos c:\janus" to get the rest of the Janus files to your hard drive.
 Appendix E shows that all of the DOS files are supposed to be in the Janus 
subdirectory, but in fact, the following four files are in the \dos subdirectory:
  keyboard.com, keyboard.sys, emm.sys, and bbsetup.com.



@endnode
@node "Jumpers"

                                     Jumpers

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

	Jumper	Default		Purpose

	J101	Link		Enables Pipeline mode. If removed, pipeline mode 
				disabled.

	J501,	Pins 1-2	Selects the type of internal drive.
	J502			Connecting pins 1-2 designates PC drives.
	    			Connecting pins 2-3 designates AMiga drives.
				Both jumpers must be set the same.A

	J506			Enables on-board PC floppy drive access.
				If removed the floppy drive controller is disabled.

	J515	1-2		Selects which AMiga Drive is used as the shared drive.
	    			Connecting pins 1-2 designates drive DF0:
	    			Connecting pins 2-3 designates drive DF1:

	J601	Link		Enables on-board PC floppy drive access.

(The manual says only J501,J502 and J515 should normally be adjusted by the user ;)

(Pin 1 of the jumpers is indicated on the board as a pointed end of the box outlining the jumper)



            @{"  " link "Bridgeboard pic"} View bridgeboard pic

@endnode

@node "Memory"
                               Bridgeboard Memory

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

 		Minimum valid memory speeds
	----------------------------------------------------------
	|	Mode		    |   20 MHz     | 	16 Mhz   |
	----------------------------------------------------------
	|                           |              |             |
	|  Page mode & 1 wait state |	100ns	   |	120ns    |
	|                           |              |             |
	|  Page mode & 0 wait state |	 80ns	   |	100ns    |
	|                           |              |             |
	|  Normal 1 wait state	    |	 80ns	   |	100ns    |
	|                           |              |             |
	|  Normal 1 wait state	    |	not valid  |  not valid  |
	|			    |		   |             |
	----------------------------------------------------------

The bridgeboard uses "Page Mode ZIP dram" chips for its RAM.

Two types are supported;	256K x 4 ZIP chips 
			     or 1MB  x 4 ZIP chips

