@node "Specs"

                                 Bridgeboard Specs

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Function: 	Provides an IBM-PC?AT compatable coprocessor system for
		amiga computers in the A2000/3000 and 4000 series

Processor:	Intel 80386

clock Speed:	16Mhz or 20Mhz

Coprocessor:	socket for optional 80387 maths copro

Memory 		1 Mb standard, expandable to 8 Mb , more with AT slot mem

Floppy Disks:	Supports any two of the following;

			One PC-only external drive (3.5" or 5.25")

			Two PC-only  internal drives of the same type;
			( 3.5" 1.44Mb PC drive , 3.5" 720kb PC or Amiga drive,
		    	 3.5" 880Kb/1.76Mb Amiga dual-speed drive,
			 5.25" high density, 5.25" low density )

			One shared 3.5" drive ( 880Kb or 880Kb/1.76Mb dual speed)

Card Type:	Uses both Amiga Zorro bus, PC/AT and PC/XT buses. Occupies one of
		the two combined positions.

Video Display:	MDA mono text   80x25 
		CGA colour text 80x25, 40x25
		CGA graphics	640x200 2 colour
				320x200 4 colour
		( All above modes supported in Amiga windows simultaneously)A

		VGA,SVGA are available using standard PC video cards


Keyboard:	IBM-PC/XT keyboard emulation using the amiga keyboard.

Parallel Port:	IBM-PC/AT compatable centronics port emulation using the Amiga's
		parallel or serial port. Only one processor can use the port at 
		any one time. (should only be used for printers!)

ROM:		64KB At-compatable BIOS

InterProcessor	128K of shared memory; ability for PC to interrupt Amiga and
Communication:	vice versa.
		
Power:		2.5 amps @ 5.0V


@endnode



@node "Setup"

                                   Setup

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

To access the setup either press CTRL+ALT+ESC during boot up ,
or type BBSETUP at the dos prompt.

Date		The format is dd.mm.yy (day.month.year)

Time		Sets the bridgeboards real-time clock. 
		The format is hh.mm.ss (hour.minute.seconds)
		Its a 24 hour clock so rememer 3pm = 15.00.00 !!

Diskette 0/1	This corresponds to the floppy drives you have designated 
		through cable connections and jumper settings as A: and B:
		You must specify the right size fo the drive;
			720K, 1.4M, NONE, 360K or 1.2M

Hard Disk 0/1	When you select this, the right hand side of the display 
		changes to show a hard disk table. If you are installing 
		a dedicated PC hard disk, you must set the specifations 
		for the drive by choosing a hard disk type from the table. 
		Should be left at NONE for an Autoboot virtual drive.

Video		This specifies the default video mode on boot up.
		Options are;
			Color 80, MONO, VGA/EGA, Color 40
		By default this is set to 80 column colour display.
		This setting must match your PCPREFS setting for 
		default bridgebaord video mode.

System Speed	This changes the clock speed of the processor.
		Normally should be left at HIGH to maximize system's
		performance.
		Setting it to LOW will half the clock speed (useful
		when very old PC software doesnt work correctly)

DRAM wait 	Normally a wait state of 0 is set (no wait states)
     states	If slower RAM is added, you may need to change this 
		to 1

Page Mode	Normally should be left at ENABLED to maximize the
		system's performance by using Page Mode memory. 
		If you need to slow the system down for some reason (?), 
		you can set this item to disabled.
		A combination of wait state of 0 and disabled page mode 
		is not supported by the bridgrboard.

On-Board Base 	Allows you to set the amount of bridgeboard memory used as
Memory		base memory, up to a maximum of 640KB.


On-Board Ext 	Allows you to set the amount of bridgeboard memory used as
Memory		extended memory. At least 384K of memory must be available
		(not used as base memory or expanded memory) to allow 
		shadowing.Any remaining memory may be used as expanded 
		memory.

Off-board Ext	Allows you to set the amount of memory on any AT-compatable
		RAM cards used as extended memory. 

VGA/EGA 	Shadowing allows you to increase your system performance by 
Shadow		copying data from ROM to higher speed RAM memory. You 
		should usually leave shadowing enabled to maximize your 
		systems performance.

		If you have installed a VGA card in one of the Amiga PC 
		expansion slots, you should enable shadowing. If you do 
		not have a VGA card this setting will have no effect on 
		your system.


BIOS Shadow	Shadowing allows you to increase your system performance by 
		copying data from ROM to higher speed RAM memory. You 
		should usually leave shadowing enabled to maximize your 
		systems performance.

Once you have set all the items appropriately, press End to exit the setup 
utility and save your settings. To abort wihtout saving your changes, 
press Esc.

@endnode

@node "Interrupts"

                             Adding Peripherals



Memory locations to avoid:

	A0000 to AFFFF		If Janus handler load segment is set to
				A000 in PCPREFS.

	B0000 to B1FFF		If Monochrome display adapter emulation 
				is enabled in PCPREFS.

	B8000 to BFFFF		If Colour display adapter emulation 
				is enabled in PCPREFS.

	D0000 to DFFFF		If Janus handler load segment is set to
				D000 in PCPREFS.

I/O ports to avoid:

000-00F	0F0
0C0-0DE 0F1
060
601

...


Interrupts to avoid:

IRQ0	IRQ6	If on-board floppy access is enabled.
IRQ1	IRQ7	
IRQ2	IRQ8	
IRQ3	IRQ9	




@endnode
